<p>Illinois experiences a continental climate with hot, humid summers and cold, snowy winters that place substantial demands on both heating and cooling systems. Summer temperatures frequently exceed 85¬∞F with high humidity levels, while winter temperatures can drop below 0¬∞F for extended periods. This climate requires robust HVAC systems capable of maintaining comfortable indoor conditions year-round while operating efficiently across wide temperature ranges.</p>

<p>Heating typically accounts for 40-50% of annual energy consumption in Illinois homes, while cooling represents 15-25% of usage during summer months. The state's heating season extends from October through April, with peak demand occurring during January and February. Air conditioning usage peaks during July and August when heat index values often exceed 100¬∞F, particularly in urban areas like Chicago where the urban heat island effect intensifies temperature extremes.</p>

<p>Indoor air quality considerations are particularly important in Illinois due to extended periods when windows remain closed during extreme weather. High-efficiency filtration systems, proper humidity control, and adequate ventilation become critical components of comprehensive HVAC system design. Modern systems incorporate variable-speed technology and zoning capabilities that improve both comfort and energy efficiency while addressing the state's diverse climate challenges.</p>

